# 📱 Telegram Setup

Telegram is the recommended primary channel for OpenClaw agents. It is fast, reliable, available on every device, supports rich formatting, and has a straightforward bot API.

---

## Why Telegram

- Free and no usage limits for personal bots
- Works on iOS, Android, Mac, Windows, web
- Bots can send and receive messages programmatically
- Supports markdown formatting in messages
- Push notifications are reliable
- Messages persist across devices

---

## Step 1 — Create your bot

1. Open Telegram and search for **@BotFather**
2. Send `/start`
3. Send `/newbot`
4. Choose a name for your bot (e.g. "Heidi")
5. Choose a username (must end in `bot`, e.g. `heidi_yourname_bot`)
6. BotFather will give you a **token** — copy it immediately

Your token looks like: `1234567890:ABCdefGHIjklMNOpqrSTUvwxyz`

> ⚠️ Treat your bot token like a password. Never commit it to GitHub. Store it in TOOLS.md locally but keep that file out of version control.

---

## Step 2 — Get your chat ID

Your agent needs your chat ID to send messages to you directly.

1. Send a message to your new bot (anything — just say "hello")
2. Open this URL in your browser, replacing YOUR_TOKEN with your actual token:
   `https://api.telegram.org/botYOUR_TOKEN/getUpdates`
3. Look for `"chat":{"id":` in the response
4. That number is your chat ID — copy it

---

## Step 3 — Test it

Send yourself a test message from the command line:

```bash
curl -X POST "https://api.telegram.org/bot[YOUR_TOKEN]/sendMessage" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"chat_id": "[YOUR_CHAT_ID]", "text": "Hello from Heidi 🌻"}'
```

You should receive the message in Telegram immediately.

---

## Step 4 — Add to TOOLS.md

Add these to your TOOLS.md:

```
## Telegram
Bot token: [your token — keep this local, never commit]
Chat ID: [your chat ID]
Primary user handle: @[your username]
```

---

## Formatting tips for agents

Telegram supports markdown in messages. Tell your agent to use:

- `*bold*` for important items
- `_italic_` for secondary info
- `` `code` `` for commands or IDs
- Bullet points with `-` for lists
- **No markdown tables** — they do not render in Telegram. Use bullet lists instead.

---

## Receiving messages from your agent

If you want your agent to be able to receive your replies (not just send), you need to poll for updates or set up a webhook. For personal use, polling is simpler:

Your agent can check for new messages with:
```
https://api.telegram.org/bot[TOKEN]/getUpdates?offset=-1
```

For a production setup, webhooks are more reliable. See the [Telegram Bot API docs](https://core.telegram.org/bots/api) for webhook setup.

---

## Privacy note

Telegram messages are not end-to-end encrypted by default (only Secret Chats are). For a personal bot sending you briefings and reminders, this is acceptable for most people. Do not send highly sensitive information (passwords, financial account numbers) through your bot.
